column12: Electrically actuated can crusher
column13: An electrically actuated can crusher having a housing, a motor mounted within the housing and a shaft rotatable by the motor and downwardly driven thereby having a crush plate thereon. The housing also includes a bottom crush plate allowing a can to be crushed to be placed in the housing between the crush plates. The housing includes an access door which, when in the open position, deactivates the motor. In this manner, when the door is closed, the motor can be activated to lower the shaft crush plate to crush a can placed therebetween. The shaft crush plate may include a lever movable in a slot in the housing to align the shaft crush plate in its movement and a reversing switch may be provided in the lever and slot to reverse the direction of movement of the shaft crush plate after crushing of a can.

column12: Software select and test
column13: A software-controlled select and test system for use with a spacecraft. The system reduces the assembly, integration, test time and improves performance of the payload and spacecraft by optimizing the performance using standardized algorithms. The system also reduces the DC power required by the spacecraft, and the thermal dissipation, battery size, solar array size and mass of the spacecraft. This is achieved by optimizing traveling wave tube amplifiers for each channel instead of meeting minimum power requirement over the entire range, wherein most channels have excess power. A serial interface adapter performs the optimization functions via software.

column12: Dual antenna null elimination
column13: RF signal nulling and loss of RF lock (i.e., loss of a communications or command link) is resolved by changing the phase of signals derived from first and second (+Z and -Z) antennas so that they add in phase instead of canceling. This is accomplished automatically by using a computer or processor to measure the RF signal level output by a receiver and change the phase of the incoming signal using a phase shifter to achieve the highest level. A squelch circuit in the receiver is used to determine the maximum obtainable RF signal level. The squelch level is compared in a computer to a threshold when the system looks for a higher squelch level. The phase of the phase shifter is changed using a computer to maximize the received signal level. A feedback loop from the receiver through the computer to the phase shifter provides a path to shift the phase of the incoming RF signal in one of the paths so the respective signals add instead of cancel, which eliminates the signal nulling problem.

column12: A New or Improved Ball or Float Valve
column13: 20,187. Ames. R., Dodd, E., and Dodd, R. P. Sept. 19. B a l l and float valves.-A ball or float valve for regulating liquid supply comprises a casing closed at p by a water-tight cap, and bored at d to receive a valve f, which is seated at e at the top of a bib c. The valve f fits the casing loosely, and is provided with a groove o and, if desired, other grooves leading to a chamber f<1> in which is another valve g, of leather or of metal, operated by a spindle h oE triangular or other section so as to allow liquid to pass downwards freely. The spindle h is actuated by a float lever j, and may or may not be provided with a slotted piece n to retain the lever j in case the valves stick. Liquid enters from the inlet b, passes into the space above the valves, and presses them on to their seats. If the valve g be lifted, fluid pressure is released in the chamber f<1>, and so the main valve is forced open. When the lever j rises, the valve g closes by gravity and the main valve slowly falls, avoiding shock. The facings of the valves are renewable, and may be of leather or of metal.

column12: Improvements relating to Sluice or like Operating Mechanism for Sewage or other Fluid Mains.
column13: 25,090. Dodd, E., Dodd, R., and Wicks, J. T. Oct. 28. Actuating. - In sluice-operating mechanism for sewage or other mains that discharge into tidal water or reservoirs &c. in which the level rises and falls, the mechanism is so operated that the main discharges only during ebb or fall of level in the reservoir. The valve a, Figs. 1 and 2, which controls through pipes c the supply of hydraulic pressure to the operating - mechanism of the sluice t is operated by rack-and-pinion mechanism, which is actuated by a float n only during a portion of the rise and fall thereof. The float n is connected to a counterweight o by a cord m which passes over pulleys l, p. Two wheels f are each mounted through one-way clutches on the shaft g in such a manner that, on the wheel l rotating in one direction, one of the wheels f is rotated, and on the reverse movement the other wheel is rotated. These wheels f engage racks k which are connected to the valve-rod b. Each rack k is of such length that it disengages with the wheel as soon as the valve is completely moved, and at the same time brings the other rack into engagement with the other wheel, the result being that the valve is moved only during the first part of the movement of the float in each direction. To prevent the sluice from being opened when the height of water outside is above that in the sewer, the device shown in Figs. 1 and 9 is provided. A pair of cylinders w, each containing a bell-shaped piston x floating in mercury, are connected by a lever y which operates a valve 3 in the pipe c supplying pressure fluid through the valve a to the sluiceoperating mechanism. The chambers formed by the pistons and cylinders are connected one by the tubes 4 with the well r, and the other by the tube 5 to the sewer. When the tide rises above the level of the water in the sewer, the pressure due to the rise of water in the tube 4 raises the piston and closes the valve 3 until the level of water in the sewer is higher than that in the well r, whereupon the reverse action takes place. Consequently if, at the reversal of the tide, the level in the sewer is below that of the sea, the sluice valve does not open.

column13: Vorrichtung, umfassend: mehrere CPUs (102, 104), die über einen Speicher-Controller-Hub (106) mit einem DRAM-Speicher (108, 406) mit mehreren Speicherbänken gekoppelt sind, wobei jede der CPUs mehrere DRAM-Verfolgungsregister (204) aufweist; wobei jede der CPUs (102, 104) eingerichtet ist, als Antwort auf Empfangen (302) einer Snoop-Adresse (202) von einer der anderen CPUs (102, 104) oder anderen Agenten die Snoop-Adresse (202) mittels eines Bankdekodierers (208) zu dekodieren (304), um eine der Speicherbänke, auf die die andere CPU zugreift, zu bestimmen, und ferner eingerichtet ist, anhand der bestimmten Speicherbank eines der DRAM-Verfolgungsregister (204) zu bestimmen, mehrere Seitenadressenbits der Snoop-Adresse (202) mittels eines Komparators (210) mit dem Inhalt des DRAM-Verfolgungsregisters (204) zu vergleichen (306), um zu bestimmen, ob eine der Snoop-Adresse (202) entsprechende Seite des DRAM-Speichers (108, 406) geöffnet ist, und, falls keine Übereinstimmung vorliegt, eine geöffnete Seite der Speicherbank zu schließen, eine der Snoop-Adresse (202) entsprechende Seite zu öffnen und die Snoop-Adresse (202) in das DRAM-Verfolgungsregister (204) zu laden; und wobei jede der CPUs (102, 104) ferner eingerichtet ist, Adressen ausgehender Transaktionen in einer Transaktionswarteschlange in DRAM-Verfolgungsregister (204), die den Speicherbänken der Adressen der Transaktionen entsprechen, zu laden und die ausgehenden Transaktionen in der Transaktionswarteschlange anhand bereits geöffneter Seiten zu ordnen.

column12: Method and apparatus to improve multi-CPU system performance for accesses to memory
column13: Methods and apparatuses for improving processor performance in a multi-processor system by optimizing accesses to memory. Processors can track the state of a memory such that the memory can be efficiently utilized in a multi-processor system including the ability to decode incoming snoop addresses from other processors, comparing them to contents of a memory tracking register(s), and updating tracking register(s) appropriately. Likewise, the transactions from other non-processor bus agents and/or bus mastering devices, such as a bus bridge, memory controller, Input/output (I/O), and graphics could also be tracked.

column12: Early power-down digital memory device and method
column13: Methods and devices for a memory system are disclosed. A digital memory device can receive power-down commands during the pendency of an active-mode command such as a burst read or write, that is, early. The device shuts down some circuitry, such as address and command registers, immediately upon receipt of the early power-down command. Other device components, e.g., those involved in servicing the burst read or write, remain active at least until their portion of the command has been completed. In some embodiments, the early power-down command can be issued concurrently with an active-mode command as an option to that command, freeing a memory controller from having to schedule and issue power-down commands separately. Significant power savings, as compared to those obtained with prior-art memory device power-down modes, are possible.

column12: SYSTEMS AND METHODS FOR COSMETICS PRODUCTS RETAIL DISPLAYS
column13: A system and method for electronically managing display components for cosmetics products. The system and method increase automation and efficiency in the operations of the computer networks, graphical user interfaces and databases for cosmetics retail displays to be responsive to retail store and customer requirements and increase performance of such systems. The system integrates information from various, often disparate and remotely located systems and databases, involved in the designing, manufacturing, producing, allocating and/or delivering components of cosmetics products retail displays to a diverse set of retail store locations. Customizations of cosmetics retail displays at various retail store locations are automated and facilitated based on cosmetics products retail sales performance at the various retail store locations. Users of such a system are provided information to more efficiently provide cosmetics retail displays and components, and supply updates to such displays according to current product data, inventory and brand or manufacturer requirements.

column12: Mechanism for enabling multi-bit counter values to reliably cross between clocking domains
column13: A queue structure for transmitting a multiple-bit signal from a first sub-system operating in a first clocking domain in a computer system to a second sub-system operating in a second clocking domain in the computer system is disclosed. The queue structure comprises a queue data latch having a plurality of storage elements, wherein each of the plurality of storage elements can store the multiple-bit signal from the first sub-system. A load pointer is used for generating a first multiple-bit count indicating one of the plurality of storage element for storing the multiple-bit signal. A synchronization unit is coupled to the load pointer for receiving the first multiple-bit count. The synchronization unit outputs the multiple-bit count at the second sub-system when the multiple-bit signal is ready to be sampled in the second clocking domain.

column12: Weighing machine for filling containers with predetermined weights of material

[Also in Divisions B8 and G1] In a packaging machine the drive means includes a main cam-shaft 58 on which is mounted a one-revolution clutch 68, which includes a ratchet 348 and spring-pressed pawl 350 pivotally mounted in a pawl carrier disc 352 rotating with cam-shaft 58. A pawl stop 354 can disengage the pawl 350, and is connected to compressed-air drive means; if the scales weighing packages in the machine make their weight in time, the pawl stop 354 is retracted and the machine continues to cycle. A roller (364) mounted on arm 360 co-operates with a cut-out (365) on disc 352. If the pawl stop is actuated to cause the clutch to disengage, the roller 364 is urged into the cut-out (365) to stop shaft 58 in a " zero " position. column12: Early power-down digital memory device and method
column13: Methods and devices for a memory system are disclosed. A digital memory device can receive power-down commands during the pendency of an active-mode command such as a burst read or write, that is, early. The device shuts down some circuitry, such as address and command registers, immediately upon receipt of the early power-down command. Other device components, e.g., those involved in servicing the burst read or write, remain active at least until their portion of the command has been completed. In some embodiments, the early power-down command can be issued concurrently with an active-mode command as an option to that command, freeing a memory controller from having to schedule and issue power-down commands separately. Significant power savings, as compared to those obtained with prior-art memory device power-down modes, are possible.

column12: Preparation of Plastic Substances and the like from Protein Containing Materials.
column13: 15,316. Dodd, R., and Humphries, H. B. P. July 3. Plastic compositions containing proteins &c. - A composition resembling horn, ivory, corozo nut, &c. is made from the protein matter of the soya bean. The bulk of the oil is removed. and the resulting meal is macerated in water; most of the insoluble and unemulsifiable matter is removed, and a coagulant is added to the liquid. The preferred coagulant is aluminium sulphate with or without an acid, and with or without formalin. In an example, 1 kg. of soya meal is macerated with water. The liquid is filtered or decanted, and warmed to 120‹ F. Colouring-matter is added and then a solution containing 100 grm. of aluminium sulphate and 20 cc. of formalin. The coagulate is strained off and moulded, the articles thus obtained being treated in a weak formaldehyde bath and dried. An alternative coagulant consists of 40 grams of aluminium sulphate, 20 cc. of hydrochloric acid, and 20 cc. of formalin in 250 cc. of water. Filling, hardening, or colouring materials may be introduced at any convenient stage of the process.

column12: METHOD OF MAKING A GRADED STENCIL
column13: 1276811 Photo-masks R C A CORPORATION 26 Jan 1970 [24 Jan 1969] 3579/70 Headings G2A G2J and G2M [Also in Divisions B6 and H1] Graded stencils (i.e. photo-masks) for use in the manufacture of shadow-mask cathode ray tubes having an array of opaque or transparent areas on a transparent or opaque background respectively, the sizes of the areas having a progressive variation from a maximum at the centre of the array to a minimum at the edges thereof, are prepared by a process comprising (1) exposing a light-sensitive film to a pattern which forms on the film an array of lighted areas of uniform size, the exposure time of at least the areas in the array varying from a maximum at the centre to a minimum at the edges, and (2) developing, specifically a hexagonal pattern of uniformly sized dots is mechanically plotted thus forming a fragmentary positive stencil, which is photographically reduced to form a negative stencil which is photographically reduced and stepped to form a positive stencil having dots whose size is equal to the smallest size required in the shadow mask; the positive stencil is used to form a corresponding negative stencil which is used together with the shutter described below to form either the required graded positive stencil or a negative stencil which is used to form the required graded positive stencil. The exposure may be effected in a single step; alternatively it may consist of a uniform exposure to produce dots of a uniform size and then a radially variable overall exposure. The shutter, Fig. 8 comprises a shutter plate 41 having an aperture 43 especially shaped to produce the required exposure time variation. The plate 41 is fixed above an aperture 46, to an opaque plate 45 rotatably mounted on a support platform 47 via rollers 47 and 51. In use, plate 45 and hence aperture 43 is rotated 465 times to contact expose stationary stencil 25, as described above.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the production of silver-halide photographic emulsions
column13: 651,318. Photographic emulsions. ILFORD, Ltd. Nov. 5, 1948, No. 28859. Addition to 585,758. [Class 98 (ii)] A photographic emulsion is prepared by forming by double decomposition a suspension of silver halide in an aqueous solution of gelatine and adding thereto, at a low pH value, sufficient of an aromatic sulphonate which is not surfaceactive but has a hydrophobic group in the anion to cause precipitation of the gelatine phase containing the silver halide, separating the so-formed gelatine/aromatic sulphonate complex containing silver halide, washing the separated complex, and redispersing in a predominantly aqueous or predominantly organic liquid medium to form the emulsion. The aromatic sulphonate may be used in admixture with an anion soap. The complex may be used to form a highly concentrated emulsion for drying. The emulsion may be ripened before formation of the complex, and the emulsion formed by re-dispersion may be digested before coating. The aromatic sulphonate may be sodium naphthalene 1- or 2-monosulphonate, disodium naphthalene-1:5-disulphonate, trisodium naphthalene - 1 : 3 : 5 - trisulphonate, a naphthol sulphonate, or a dye such as Tartrazine. In example (1), the pH of a ripened fine-grain silver bromide emulsion is adjusted to 2.0 with sulphuric acid, an aqueous solution of sodium naphthalene-2-monosulphonate is added, the supernatant liquid is decanted from the precipitate, and the latter is dispersed in 40 per cent aqueous alcohol adjusted to pH 5.0 with alkali. The complex is re-precipitated by addition of 98 per cent ethyl alcohol, the supernatant liquid is decanted, the precipitate is soaked in water, and re-dispersed in aqueous gelatine solution. The resulting emulsion is digested and coated. In example (2), the procedure is similar using sodium 2 - naphthol - 6 - sulphonate, and in example (3), the procedure is similar to example (1) using an original emulsion of much greater gelatine strength. Specification 580,504 is referred to.

column12: PACKAGE FOR FOAMING BEVERAGE, AND PACKAGING METHOD
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To manufacture a package at a low cost by using a hollow insert which can float on a beverage, and efficiently form foam at the time of unsealing by a simple structure by a method wherein a fluid which pressurizes a first chamber of the container is fed from an opening of a second chamber of a hollow insert, and pressurized, and the pressurized gas is jetted into a beverage in the first chamber from an opening. SOLUTION: During a rotating motion of a container 10, a capsule 1 is lifted from a lower position to a rising position, and a narrowed opening 7 is lifted to a sufficient height where the opening 7 can directly communicate with a gas in a head space 15. As the pressure in the head space 15 rises by an evaporation of liquid nitrogen 16, the pressure in a second chamber 3 of the capsule 1 increases in the same manner. Then, when the open top of the container 10 is sealed, the capsule 1 is located at a lowered position, and as a result of the buoyancy balancing adjustment, the direction of the capsule 1 becomes a state wherein the narrowed opening 7 is immersed in a beverage 6, when the package 10 is unsealed, the fluid in the second chamber 3 is jetted from the capsule 1 through the narrowed opening 7.

column12: A method of packaging a beverage containing gas in solution and a beverage package
column13: A method of packaging a beverage having gas in solution and a beverage package has a container 10 containing the beverage 6 to form a headspace 15. Floating on the beverage 6 is a hollow spherical capsule having a restricted aperture 7. During sealing of the container 10 by a top 20 the headspace 15 is pressurised (by a nitrogen dose 16) and during such pressurisation the insert 1 is raised relative to its natural floating position on the beverage 6 to ensure that the aperture 7 communicates with the headspace 15 to pressurise the chamber of that insert. The aforementioned raising of the insert 1 is preferably achieved by subjecting the insert to a centrifugal force during rotation of the container in seaming the top 20 thereto or by magnetic attraction. Following pressurisation of the headspace 15 the insert is lowered to float naturally on the beverage 6 with its aperture 7 submerged. During pressurisation the insert 1 may take in a minimal volume of beverage from the container. When the container is opened by ring pull 25 a pressure differential develops causing fluid under pressure to be ejected from the insert 1 through the aperture 7 into the beverage 6 for liberating gas from solution and the development of froth on the beverage.

column12: Method of packaging a beverage containing gas in solution and a beverage package
column13: A method of packaging a beverage having gas in solution and a beverage package has a container  10  containing the beverage  6  to form a headspace  15  . Floating on the beverage  6  is a hollow spherical capsule having a restricted aperture  7  . During sealing of the container  10  by a top  20  the headspace  15  is pressurised (by a nitrogen dose  16  ) and during such pressurisation the insert  1  is raised relative to its natural floating position on the beverage  6  to ensure that the aperture  7  communicates with the headspace  15  to pressurise the chamber of that insert. The aforementioned raising of the insert  1  is preferably achieved by subjecting the insert to a centrifugal force during rotation of the container in seaming the top  20  thereto or by magnetic attraction. Following pressurisation of the headspace  15  the insert is lowered to float naturally on the beverage  6  with its aperture  7  submerged. During pressurisation the insert  1  may take in a minimal volume of beverage from the container. When the container is opened by ring pull  25  a pressure differential develops causing fluid under pressure to be ejected from the insert  1  through the aperture  7  into the beverage  6  for liberating gas from solution and the development of froth on the beverage.
column15: DODD CAROLE JANE;;PURDHAM ROBERT;;SARGEANT VIVIEN JANE

column12: Improved casein
column13: The properties, i.e. opacity, colour, of casein obtained from animal or vegetable sources are improved by alternately washing the precipitated and coagulated protein with water at different temperatures in the presence of a surface-active agent, which may be added prior to the coagulation, so that the coagulate swells during one washing and contracts during the next washing. The coagulate and whey are heated at a rate of increase of temperature not greater than 1 DEG C. per minute to a temperature such that the coagulate may be handled but below that at which the coagulate becomes rubbery or stringy in texture or coagulates into large masses, e.g. 60 DEG C., and is separated from the whey as quickly as possible. The coagulate is then washed with water at 40-50 DEG C., separated from the wash water, washed with water at a temperature below 20 DEG C. and separated therefrom, the sequence being repeated a plurality of times. Suitable surfaceactive agents are anionic, cationic, or non-ionic agents, the latter class being capable of forming water-soluble complexes with calcium and other heavy metals in which the metal is present in a unionized form, e.g. alkylated phenol ethylene oxide condensate, condensates of long-chain fatty alcohols and ethylene oxide which possesses a polyethylene glycol chain.

column12: Compositions for reducing odor on skin
column13: The present invention relates to an aqueous odor-absorbing composition which is safe for use on human skin comprising from about 0.1 % to about 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.5 % to about 30 %, by weight of the composition, of a linear dimethicone having a nominal viscosity of 350 centistokes or less; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can also comprise one or more of the following optional components: low molecular weight polyols; water-soluble antimicrobial preservatives; zinc salts; water-soluble polymers; soluble carbonate and/or bicarbonate salts; chelating agents; zeolites; activated carbon; and mixtures thereof. The present invention also relates the use of the aforementioned compositions in reducing body, vaginal, and or environmental odors on skin. The composition can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.

column12: Automated three nail gun tool dolly
column13: A new and improved automated gun tool dolly which comprises a plurality of nail guns, such as, for example, three nail guns, which are mounted upon a horizontally movable carriage assembly in a vertically and horizontally staggered mode so as to be disposed within a diagonal array. Movement of the carriage assembly along horizontally oriented guide rails is automatically controlled, such as, for example, by means of a programmable logic controller (PLC), such that the three nail guns are sequentially and continuously disposed at predetermined firing positions at which the nail guns are sequentially fired so as to insert nails within predetermined regions of 2×4 or 2×6 plate, header, or footer members of a wall panel or wall structure.

column12: PROCEDIMIENTO PARA ENVASAR UNA BEBIDA QUE CONTIENE GAS EN SOLUCION.
column13: UN PROCEDIMIENTO PARA ENVASAR UNA BEBIDA CON GAS EN SOLUCION Y UN ENVASE DE BEBIDA CONSTA DE UN RECIPIENTE 10 QUE CONTIENE LA BEBIDA 6 PARA FORMAR UN ESPACIO DE AIRE 15. FLOTANDO EN LA BEBIDA 6 HAY UNA CAPSULA ESFERICA HUECA CON UNA ABERTURA LIMITADA 7. DURANTE EL SELLADO DEL RECIPIENTE 10 POR UNA TAPA 20 SE PRESURIZA EL ESPACIO DE AIRE 15 (MEDIANTE UNA DOSIS DE NITROGENO 16), Y DURANTE ESTA PRESURIZACION EL INSERTO 1 SE ELEVA EN RELACION CON SU POSICION LATERAL DE FLOTAMIENTO EN LA BEBIDA 6 PARA ASEGURAR QUE LA ABERTURA 7 SE COMUNICA CON EL ESPACIO DE AIRE 15 CON OBJETO DE PRESURIZAR LA CAMARA DEL INSERTO. ESTA ELEVACION DEL INSERTO 1 SE LOGRA PREFERENTEMENTE SOMETIENDOLO A UNA FUERZA CENTRIFUGA DURANTE LA ROTACION DEL RECIPIENTE AL UNIRLE LA TAPA 20 O POR ATRACCION MAGNETICA. TRAS LA PRESURIZACION DEL ESPACIO DE AIRE 15, SE DESCIENDE EL INSERTO PARA QUE FLOTE DE MANERA NATURAL EN LA BEBIDA 6 CON SU ABERTURA 7 SUMERGIDA. DURANTE LA PRESURIZACION, EL INSERTO 1 PUEDE ADMITIR UN VOLUMEN MINIMO DE BEBIDA DEL RECIPIENTE. CUANDO EL RECIPIENTE SE ABRE TIRANDO DE UN ARO 25 SE DESARROLLA UN DIFERENCIAL DE PRESION HACIENDO QUE EL FLUIDO BAJO PRESION SALGA EXPULSADO DEL INSERTO 1 A TRAVES DE LA ABERTURA 7 A LA BEBIDA 6 PARA LIBERAR GAS DE LA SOLUCION Y FORMANDO ESPUMA EN LA BEBIDA.

column12: Dual polarisation comparator for deriving sum and difference signals
column13: Four aerial element signals, each having vertically and horizontally polarised components, are applied to the input ports of a square array of square waveguides. Two further square guides are arranged on each of opposite sides of the square array. Signal components in one (vertical) plane are coupled between the four inner guides in azimuth and elevation and signal components in the other (horizontal) plane are coupled out of the inner foul guides and into the outer guides. Selective transference is achieved by rotation of the polarisation planes. Sum and difference signals are thus obtained from the inner guides for one plane of polarisation and from the outer guides for the other.

column12: Aerosol actuators and improved aerosol assemblies
column13: According to certain embodiments of the invention, a valve guide or raised boss may be connected to or integral with a base or body of an aerosol actuator. In various embodiments, a valve guide may include a raised boss associated with a grip or body of an aerosol actuator. The valve guide or raised boss may align a manifold with a valve when an aerosol actuator is assembled to a container containing a product. In addition, a valve guide or raised boss may limit the movement of a portion of a manifold in a defined direction or defined plane such that the load on a valve by a manifold is controlled. For example, a valve guide may ensure a top load on a valve during actuation or may minimize side loads on a valve during actuation.

column12: ELECTROMAGNETIC INTERFERENCE SHIELDED PANEL AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURE THEREFOR
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide an electromagnetic interference shielded panel which shields the content in a case from electromagnetic interference, by shielding electromagnetic waves entering the case to accommodate devices, such as electrical devices that receive adverse effects due to electromagnetic waves, and to provide a manufacturing method for the panel.

SOLUTION: A panel 20 comprises one or more frame members, having a rib serving as a sacrifical material, when a first skin member 120 is welded to the frame member. Before a core member 160 and a second skin member 140 are connected to the first skin member and a frame assembly, the first skin member is welded to the frame member of the frame assembly.

column12: Magnetron cathode
column13: A magnetron includes a cathode 1, coaxially disposed within anode 2, having end regions 10 and 11 which are electron emissive during operation and a central region 12 which is substantially non-emissive. Such an arrangement has been found to give improved performance. The non-emissive region preferably occupies less than one third of the total axial extent of the cathode. In various other cathode configurations disclosed, Figs. 2-7 (not shown), a plurality of symmetrically disposed non-emissive regions may be provided, or the cathode surface may be grooved with some of the grooves filled with emissive material, the remaining grooves being left empty or filled with non-emissive material. <IMAGE>

column12: Acrylamide terpolymer shale stabilizing additive for low viscosity oil and gas drilling operations
column13: A low viscosity drilling fluid and method for stabilizing a downhole shale formation are disclosed. The fluid comprises an aqueous solution of a partialy transamidated hydrolyzed acrylamide copolymer, potassium chloride, a weighting agent and an optional viscosifying agent. The copolymer comprises from about 50 to about 98 mole percent primary amide functionality, from about 0.1 to about 15 mole percent secondary amide functionality and from about 2 to about 50 mole percent of the acrylate salt. The drilling fluid has a density out from about 8 to about 18 pounds per gallon and a viscosity of from about 5 to about 30 centistokes.

column12: Glucose measurement prediction using stacked machine learning models
column13: Glucose measurements and glucose impact event prediction using a stack of machine learning models are described. The CGM platform includes stacked machine learning models such that an output generated by one of the machine learning models may be provided as an input to another of the machine learning models. The plurality of machine learning models includes at least one model trained to generate a glucose measurement prediction and another model trained to generate an event prediction for an upcoming time interval. Each machine learning model of the stacked machine learning models is configured to generate a respective output when provided as input at least one of a glucose measurement provided by a CGM system worn by the user or additional data describing user behavior or affecting other aspects of future glucose of the person. The predictions may then be output, such as by transmitting and/or displaying notifications regarding the corresponding predictions.

column12: Coaxial output arrangement for a magnetron
column13: A magnetron output arrangement includes a coaxial output adapted to be coupled in an endfire configuration to a rectangular waveguide. The waveguide has a flange for mating with the magnetron output arrangement. The coaxial output includes a central conductor. The output arrangement further includes a plate located in a predetermined position with respect to the central conductor. The plane of the plate is arranged to be substantially perpendicular to the axis of the coaxial output. The plate is located a predetermined distance from the end of the central conductor, such that the coaxial output in use couples with the plate so that the output coupling is substantially the same regardless of the type of waveguide flange employed.

column12: PROSTHESIS WITH ARTIFICIAL LIGAMENT
column13: A prosthetic device comprising a bearing component (2, 4) for connection to a bone (3, 6), the bearing component (2, 4) replacing part or all of a human or animal joint, and a prosthetic ligament (8) which is connected to or passes through the bearing component (2, 4). Preferably, the joint comprises a human knee joint and the first and second bearing components comprise a tibial bearing component (4) and a femoral bearing component (2) respectively, and the prosthetic ligament (8) at one end is connected to or passes through the tibial component (4) and at the other end is connected to or passes through the femoral component (2). The present invention can be used with a fixed bearing prosthetic knee or a mobile bearing knee using a meniscal component (10).

column12: Coaxial output arrangement for a magnetron
column13: A magnetron 10 has a co-axial output13 which comprises a central conductor 14 and terminates in a probe 16. Power is transmitted from the magnetron 10, via the coaxial line 13, to a rectangular waveguide 17. The co-axial output 13 further comprises a plate member19 located in a predetermined position with respect to the central conductor 14. The plate member 19 has an aperture (22, figure 4) with an edge 20 arranged to overlap approximately half of the probe 16 in a spaced relationship (figure 4), such that the waveguide 17 and coaxial line 13 are arranged in an 'end-fire' configuration. This arrangement allows the coupling to be optimised as the distance between the end of the probe 16 and the plate member 19 is fixed. Additionally the arrangement may be provided with a tuning stub (23, figure 5) for tuning the magnetron output.

column12: MAGNETRON ARRANGEMENTS
column13: A magnetron arrangement has a coaxial output (13) including a central conductor (14). The output further comprises a plate (19) located in a predetermined position with respect to the central conductor. The plate optimises the coupling of energy between the magnetron (11) and a rectangular waveguide (17). Previously, the central conductor of the coaxial output was arranged in a predetermined position with respect to a wall of the waveguide, but it was found that the amount of coupling thus produced was dependent on the type of end flange fused at the end of the waveguide.

column12: Nanoclustered magnetic materials for high moment write pole applications
column13: The present invention includes magnetic write elements with portions formed a nanophase high magnetic moment material to enable further increases in areal density in magnetic recording. The nanophase deposited high magnetic moment material comprises coated nanoclusters and nanolaminated cluster films that are deposited to form nanophase high magnetic moment material portions of a write pole and SUL layer in perpendicular recording media. The nanophase write poles exhibit high magnetic moments and are generally compatible with conventional writer head fabrication techniques.

column12: Composition and method for treating cognitive impairments in down syndrom subjects
column13: Compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit for use as a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The use of these compounds is disclosed. Pharmaceutical compositions for such treatment can comprise these compounds or suitable pharmaceutically acceptable salt thereof, a polyethoxylated castor oil and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). Methods are disclosed for enhancing cognitive function, or treating or lessening the severity of cognitive impairments, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome by administering to a subject in need thereof a pharmaceutically effective amount of one or more of these compounds.

column13: L'invention concerne des dérivés indoliques répondant à la formule générale I dans laquelle : > - R représente un atome d'hydrogène, un atome d'halogène, un groupe alkyle en C à C linéaire ou ramifié ou un groupe aryle et en particulier phényle, ou encore un groupe arylalkyle en C à C - R représente un atome d'hydrogène, un atome d'halogène, un groupe alkyle en C à C linéaire ou ramifié, un radical hydroxy, un groupe alkoxy en C à C , un groupe aryle, alkylaryloxy, arylalkyloxy, aryloxy en particulier benzyloxy, ou encore un groupement NO ; - n = 1, 2 ou 3 ; - Ar représente un radical aryle mono- ou polycyclique éventuellement substitué par un ou plusieurs atome (s) d'halogène, ou groupa (s) alkyle en C à C , ou par des groupes alkoxy en à C ou encore un groupe aryle tel que phényle, en particulier des radicaux choisis parmi les radicaux phényle, naphtyle et phénantrényle ; > - R R représentent indépendamment l'un de l'autre un atome d'hydrogène ou un groupe alkyle en C à C linéaire ramifié, ou un groupe alkoxy en C à C ; ainsi que leurs sels avec des acides pharmaceutiquement acceptables sous forme d'un mélange racémique, de mélanges d'isomères optiques dans lesquels l'isomère R est prépondérant, ou de son isomère R optiquement pur, à l exception toutefois du composé de formule I sous forme racémique dans lequel : - R = R = R = H - R = F et Ar = naphtyle et à l'exception également du composé de formule I sous toutes ses formes énantiomériques dans laquelle : - R = R = R = R = H et - Ar = naphtyle.

A presente invenção inclui o uso de composições de absorção de odor para o controle de maus odores ambientais sobre a pele, em que a composição de absorção de odor compreende ciclodextrina não-complexada, um veículo aquoso, perfume volátil hidrofílico e, opcionalmente, uma fase oleosa e um ou mais tensoativos.
column15: LUCAS JULIET MARIE;;TRINH TOAN;;DODD MICHAEL THOMAS;;BARTOLO ROBERT GREGORY

column12: Methods for controlling environmental odors on the body using compositions comprising uncomplexed cyclodextrins
column13: The present invention encompasses a method of controlling environmental malodors on the body comprising the application to the skin of a composition comprising from about 0.1% to about 5%, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.1% to about 36%, by weight of the composition, of an oil phase selected from the group consisting of emollients, moisturizers, and skin protectants; one or more surfactants each having a hydrophilic/lipophilic balance of about 8 to 18 and wherein each surfactant, when combined with an aqueous cyclodextrin solution, provides no less than 25% of odor capture as an aqueous cyclodextrin solution; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.

column12: COMPOSICIONES EN DOS FASES LIBRES DE PERFUME Y METODOS PARA PRODUCIR EL OLOR CORPORAL Y AMBIENTAL
column13: La presente invención se relaciona con una composiciónabsorbente de olor que contiene: a) desde 0.1% hasta 5% en peso de la composición de ciclodextrina no complexada, soluble en agua solubilizada; b) desde 0.1% hasta 36% en peso de la composición de una fase de aceite seleccionada del grupo consistente e emolientes, humectantes y protectores para la piel; c) uno o más surfactantes que tienen un equilibrio hidrófilo/lipófilo de 8 a 18 y donde cada surfactante cuando se combina con una solución acuosa de ciclodextrina, provee no menos que 25% de un nivel de captura de olor como solución acuosa de ciclodextrina; y d) un portador acuoso; donde la composición es segura para uso sobre la piel. Adicionalmente se relaciona también con métodos para reducir el olor que comprende la aplicación a la piel de la anterior composición, depositada sobre un medio dispensador flexible.

column12: COMPOSITION AND METHOD FOR TREATING COGNITIVE IMPAIRMENTS IN DOWN SYNDROM SUBJECTS
column13: This application relates to compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit for use as a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The present application also relates to the use of compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit for the preparation of a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The application further relates to pharmaceutical compositions for treating cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome comprising a compound having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit, or suitable pharmaceutically acceptable salt thereof, a polyethoxylated castor oil and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). The present application also describes methods for enhancing cognitive function, or treating or lessening the severity of cognitive impairments, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome by administering to a subject in need thereof a pharmaceutically effective amount of one or more compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit. More particularly, the present application is concerned with the treatment of cognitive impairments, such as impairment in memory, learning capacity or both, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome.

column12: Nanoclustered magnetic materials for high moment write pole applications
column13: The present invention includes magnetic write elements with portions formed a nanophase high magnetic moment material to enable further increases in areal density in magnetic recording. The nanophase deposited high magnetic moment material comprises coated nanoclusters and nanolaminated cluster films that are deposited to form nanophase high magnetic moment material portions of a write pole and SUL layer in perpendicular recording media. The nanophase write poles exhibit high magnetic moments and are generally compatible with conventional writer head fabrication techniques.

column12: Dispenser for extrudable material
column13: A hand dispenser for dispensing an extrudable material includes a housing for holding the extrudable material, along with a pistol grip handle. A trigger member is mounted adjacent the pistol grip handle for movement in a path toward and away therefrom to incrementally effect a metered dispensing of the extrudable material. An adjustable stop cam is mounted in the path of movement of the trigger member. The stop cam has different cam portions engageable by the trigger member and is effective to limit movement of the trigger member to different degrees and, thereby, vary the metered amount of dispensed material. A piston rod has a series of ratcheting teeth on at least two different sides of the rod engageable by a drive pawl operatively associated with the trigger member. The ratcheting teeth in one series thereof has a spacing different from the spacing of the ratcheting teeth in the other series thereof. Therefore, the multiple series of ratcheting teeth provide multiple settings of the dispenser for each setting of the adjustable stop cam.

column12: Ink and method of conducting an examination
column13: An ink and method of conducting an examination suitable for reducing the likelihood that the students' answers on paper-based examinations may be changed at a later time prior to being graded. The ink includes a solution of marking particles, a suspension material, and a preserving material. A mark made with the ink is initially erasable for a predetermined period of time after the mark is formed and after the expiration of the predetermined period of time the mark is not erasable. The method of conducting an examination includes providing an ink to an individual, and then providing questions to an individual wherein the individual indicates answers to the questions by producing marks with the ink.

column12: Dissolution Testing Machine
column13: A dissolution testing machine has a container for a liquid and a holder for pellets, means supporting the holder within the container and drive means enabling the holder to be reciprocated via its support means so that solvent flushes into and out of the holder. The holder may be a mesh tube, or a solid walled tube, closed at both ends by an apertured member. A set of containers may receive the holder successively, each container containing a solvent of the same or different characteristics. The container or containers may be supported in a temperature-controlled bath.

column12: Methods for controlling environmental odors on the body using compositions comprising uncomplexed cyclodextrins and perfume
column13: The present invention encompasses a method of controlling environmental odors on the body comprising the application to the skin of a composition comprising from about 0.1% to about 5%, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.1% to about 36%, by weight of the composition, of an oil phase selected from the group consisting of emollients, moisturizers, and skin protectants; one or more surfactants; from about 0.004% to about 2%, by weight of the composition, of a hydrophilic, volatile perfume composition; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.

column12: Composition and method for treating cognitive impairments in down syndrome subjects
column13: This application relates to compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A  receptors containing the α5 subunit for use as a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The present application also relates to the use of compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A  receptors containing the α5 subunit for the preparation of a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The application further relates to pharmaceutical compositions for treating cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome comprising a compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A  receptors containing the α5 subunit, or suitable pharmaceutically acceptable salt thereof, a polyethoxylated castor oil and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). The present application also describes methods for enhancing cognitive function, or treating or lessening the severity of cognitive impairments, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome by administering to a subject in need thereof a pharmaceutically effective amount of one or more compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A  receptors containing the α5 subunit. More particularly, the present application is concerned with the treatment of cognitive impairments, such as impairment in memory, learning capacity or both, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome.

column12: INK AND METHOD OF CONDUCTING AN EXAMINATION
column13: An ink and method of conducting an examination suitable for reducing the likelihood that the students' answers on paper-based examinations may be changed at a later time prior to being graded. The ink includes a solution of marking particles, a suspension material, and a preserving material. A mark made with the ink is initially erasable for a predetermined period of time after the mark is formed and after the expiration of the predetermined period of time the mark is not erasable. The method of conducting an examination includes providing an ink to an individual, and then providing questions to an individual wherein the individual indicates answers to the questions by producing marks with the ink.

column12: COMPOSITION AND METHOD FOR TREATING COGNITIVE IMPAIRMENTS IN DOWN SYNDROM SUBJECTS
column13: Compounds having inverse agonist functional selectivity for GABA A receptors containing the α5 subunit for use as a medicament in the treatment of cognitive impairments in subjects suffering from Down syndrome. The use of these compounds is disclosed. Pharmaceutical compositions for such treatment can comprise these compounds or suitable pharmaceutically acceptable salt thereof, a polyethoxylated castor oil and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). Methods are disclosed for enhancing cognitive function, or treating or lessening the severity of cognitive impairments, in subjects suffering from Down syndrome by administering to a subject in need thereof a pharmaceutically effective amount of one or more of these compounds.

column12: Managing primitive program vertex attributes as per-attribute arrays
column13: Systems and methods for compiling high-level primitive programs are used to generate primitive program micro-code for execution by a primitive processor. A compiler is configured to produce micro-code for a specific target primitive processor based on the target primitive processor's capabilities. The compiler supports features of the high-level primitive program by providing conversions for different applications programming interface conventions, determining output primitive types, initializing attribute arrays based on primitive input profile modifiers, and determining vertex set lengths from specified primitive input types.

column12: DETERGENT ADDITIVES FOR LUBRICATING OIL COMPOSITIONS
column13: Use as a detergent in a lubricating oil composition of an oil-soluble hydrocarbyl phenol aldehyde condensate having the following structure: (see above formula) wherein n is 0 to 10, preferably 1 to 8, more preferably 2 to 6, and most preferably 3 to 5; Y is a divalent bridging group, and is preferably a hydrocarbyl group, preferably having from 1 to 4 carbon atoms; and R is a hydrocarbyl group having from 4 to 30, preferably 8 to 18, and most preferably 9 to 15 carbon atoms. The oil-soluble hydrocarbyl phenol aldehyde condensate has a weight average molecular weight (Mw) of 1250 to 1680, as measured by MALDI-TOF (Matrix Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization- Time of Flight) mass spectrometry.

column12: CLEANING ADDITIVE FOR LUBRICATION OIL COMPOSITION
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a new cleaning additive that is free from sulfur and metals(mineral content in other words).

SOLUTION: As a cleaning agent in a lubricant oil composition are, is used an oil soluble hydrocarbyl phenol aldehyde condensate having a structure of the formula (wherein n is 0 to 10, Y is a divalent crosslinking group and the R is a 4 to 30 C hydrocarbyl). The weight average molecular weight (Mw) of this oil-soluble hydrocarbyl phenol-aldehyde condensate is 1250 to 1680 that is measured according to the MARDI-TOF (Matrix Assisted Laser Desorption Ionization-Time of Flight) mass analysis.

column12: Motion detector unit
column13: PCT No. PCT/GB91/02099 Sec. 371 Date Jul. 29, 1992 Sec. 102(e) Date Jul. 29, 1992 PCT Filed Nov. 27, 1991 PCT Pub. No. WO92/09905 PCT Pub. Date Jun. 11, 1992.A unit for detecting a moving person or object by means of doppler frequency shift. The unit comprises a microwave circuit board (1) accommodating an oscillator and a mixer, and an antenna board (2) carrying transmit (8) and receive (9) patch arrays. In the assembled unit the two boards (1,2) are disposed adjacent one another. Coupling between the microwave circuit and the antenna arrays is achieved by two slots (6,11) resonant at the oscillator fundamental frequency and formed in a ground plane (5) on the microwave board (1). Feed striplines (7,10,12) on the two boards (1,2) lie orthogonal to the slots (6,11) and are terminated in T-sections (15,14). The stripline/slot arrangement suppresses emission at the oscillator second harmonic frequency. column13: PCT No. PCT/GB91/02099 Sec. 371 Date Jul. 29, 1992 Sec. 102(e) Date Jul. 29, 1992 PCT Filed Nov. 27, 1991 PCT Pub. No. WO92/09905 PCT Pub. Date Jun. 11, 1992.A unit for detecting a moving person or object by means of doppler frequency shift. The unit comprises a microwave circuit board (1) accommodating an oscillator and a mixer, and an antenna board (2) carrying transmit (8) and receive (9) patch arrays. In the assembled unit the two boards (1,2) are disposed adjacent one another. Coupling between the microwave circuit and the antenna arrays is achieved by two slots (6,11) resonant at the oscillator fundamental frequency and formed in a ground plane (5) on the microwave board (1). Feed striplines (7,10,12) on the two boards (1,2) lie orthogonal to the slots (6,11) and are terminated in T-sections (15,14). The stripline/slot arrangement suppresses emission at the oscillator second harmonic frequency. The antenna board (2) has no electrical connection to the microwave circuit, enabling the radiated beam shape to be changed by simply replacing the antenna board with one having a different patch array pattern.

column12: CHILD RESISTANT AEROSOL ACTUATOR
column13: The actuator includes a shroud adapted to be situated on an aerosol container over the stem and an actuation member mounted on and moveable within the shroud to depress the stem by the application of an external force applied to the top surface of the actuation member. The actuation member includes a nozzle and a conduit for connecting the stem and the nozzle. A hood is normally positioned to block the actuation member from being moved to depress the stem. A locking member normally intersects the path of movement of the hood to lock the hood in its blocking position. The locking member has two sections both of which must be simultaneously moved to a position remote from the path of hood movement such that the hood may be moved from its blocking position, allowing the actuation member to be moved to depress the stem.

column12: Liquid metal bearing structure with enhanced sealing structure
column13: The invention relates to a liquid metal bearing structure with an enhanced sealing structure. The invention provides a bearing arrangement for an X-ray tube, the bearing arrangement comprising a journal bearing shaft having a radially projecting thrust bearing encased within a sleeve. The structure of the sleeve forms enlarged wells or voids in the sleeve that are disposed adjacent to various rotating anti-wetting seals/sealing surfaces formed between the sleeve and the shaft. The geometry of the trap is formed to retain the liquid metal/lubricating fluid within the gap defined by the bearing assembly and direct the liquid metal to flow outwardly from the gap defined between the sleeve and the shaft away from the rotating anti-wetting seal and back into the gap. This geometry allows centrifugal forces exerted on the liquid metal by rotation of the bearing structure to move the flowing-out liquid metal away from the rotating dampproof seal, thereby significantly reducing contact of the liquid metal with the seal.

column13: The present invention relates to an odor absorbing composition, which is safe for use on human skin, comprising from 0.1 % to 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from 0.1 % to 36 %, by weight of the composition, of an oil phase selected from the group consisting of emollients, moisturizers, and skin protectants; an emulsifier; and an aqueous carrier. The odor absorbing compositions of the present invention may also contain an effective amount of hydrophobic antimicrobials. The present invention also relates to the use of cyclodextrin-containing compositions for the manufacture of an odor absorbing composition, which is safe for use on skin, for controlling environmental malodors on skin and for reducing body odor and/or vaginal odor.

column12: Cache control method and apparatus.
column13: A host computer (10) is backed up by long term secondary magnetic disk storage means (14) coupled to the computer by channels (12), a storage director (16) and a control module (18). A cache memory (22) with an associated cache manager (24) are also connected to the storage director (16) for storing data which the host computer (10) is likely to require. In order to allow automatic transfer to the cache memory (22) of only that data which is likely to be required, the storage director (16) and cache manager (24) determine when accessed data from the disk storage means (14) appears to be part of sequential data because it lacks indications to the contrary, such as embedded SEEK instructions. When data lacks such counter indications, automatic transfers to the cache memory (22) occur a track at a time.

column12: COMPUTER SYSTEM AND METHOD OF OPERATION
column13: When data is called from a disk memory by a host computer, the data is examined to detect embedded commands which would indicate that the data is not part of a sequential data stream. When such negative indicators are absent (NO STAGE INDICATORS OFF, 86) and provided the total amount of requested data is not large (88), one track is staged (90) into a cache memory in anticipation of a future request. If record 1 on the track was read (92) to the host, it is likely that the request is one of a sequence of requests and a flag is set (94) to indicate this. If then it is possible to de-allocate from the cache the track having the current address less two it is known that three consecutively addressed tracks have been read and an additional track is pre-staged into the cache in anticipation of continuation of the sequence.

column12: Packaging a beverage to incorporate a floatable froth producing insert
column13: A method of packaging a beverage, especially beer, to incorporate a floatable froth producing insert comprises charging an open topped container 10 with beverage 6 to form a headspace 15 and including a hollow insert 1 that floats on the beverage. The insert has at last one restricted aperture 7, and is ballasted so that the aperture is submerged in the beverage when floating naturally. The container is then sealed, and the headspace pressurised to a pressure greater than atmospheric. During the pressurisation stage, the insert is preferably raised so that the aperture is above the level of the liquid, so that it becomes filled with gas at the same pressure as the headspace. The insert may be raised during pressurisation by rotating the container to subject the insert to a centrifugal force so that it abuts against the container wall, or it may be raised by a magnetic force. Alternatively, the insert may be kept at a raised position on the container wall using adhesive. The insert is then lowered so that it floats naturally on the beverage with the aperture submerged. When the container is opened, the gas in the insert is jetted out of the aperture into the beverage to develop froth. Beverage packages are also disclosed that include inserts with one aperture so arranged as to cause rotation of the insert during the jetting of the gas, or with two apertures arranged so that rotation of the insert is restricted during the jetting. An insert is additionally disclosed with a spherical outer surface and a wall of varying thickness serving to ballast the insert with the aperture below the beverage.

column12: Memory system and organization for host computer.
column13: A host computer (10) is backed up by magnetic disk stores (14) which may be of different types having different track lengths. The host computer is conventionally coupled tothe disk stores by channels (12), a storage director (16) and disk control modules (18). A solid-state cache memory array (22) with an associated cache manager (22) are connected to the storage director for storing tracks of data likely to be required by the host computer. In order to provide efficient utilisation of the cache memory array (22) it is arranged in domains having a length which is substantially an integral multiple of all the different track lengths. The domains are assigned to the different classes of disk storage devices (14) and reallocation is effected from time to time on the basis of actual usage.

column12: Method and system for configuring and scheduling security audits of a computer network
column13: Managing the selection and scheduling of security audits run on a computing network. The computer network is surveyed by a security audit system to determine the function and relative importance of the elements in the network. Based on function and priority, a more thorough type of security audit is selected to run against each of the network elements by the security audit system. The security audit can also be automatically scheduled based on the information gathered from the survey. Once the system runs the security audit, a vulnerability assessment can be calculated for each element in the network. The vulnerability assessment can be presented in a format that facilitates interpretation and response by someone operating the system. The vulnerability assessment can also be used to configure and schedule future security audits.

column12: COMPUTER SYSTEM AND METHOD OF OPERATION
column13: A host computer (10) is backed up by long term secondary magnetic disk storage means (14) coupled to the computer by channels (12), a storage director (16) and a control module (18). A cache memory (22) with an associated cache manager (24) are also connected to the storage director (16) for storing data which the host computer (10) is likely to require. In order to allow automatic transfer to the cache memory (22) of only that data which is likely to be required, the storage director (16) and cache manager (24) determine when accessed data from the disk storage means (14) appears to be part of sequential data because it lacks indications to the contrary, such as embedded SEEK instructions. When data lacks such counter indications, automatic transfers to the cache memory (22) occur a track at a time.

column12: HAUTGERUCHSREDUZIERUNGSKOMPOSITIONEN
column13: The present invention relates to an aqueous odor-absorbing composition which is safe for use on human skin comprising from about 0.1 % to about 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.5 % to about 30 %, by weight of the composition, of a linear dimethicone having a nominal viscosity of 350 centistokes or less; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can also comprise one or more of the following optional components: low molecular weight polyols; water-soluble antimicrobial preservatives; zinc salts; water-soluble polymers; soluble carbonate and/or bicarbonate salts; chelating agents; zeolites; activated carbon; and mixtures thereof. The present invention also relates the use of the aforementioned compositions in reducing body, vaginal, and or environmental odors on skin. The composition can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.

column12: Distributor for engine with laser ignition
column13: A distributor is described for a multi-cylinder laser ignited internal combustion engine. The distributor includes a shaft rotatable by the engine and a plurality of flat reflective surfaces on the shaft. The surfaces lie in planes normal to the axis of rotation of the shaft and are axially staggered from one another along the length of the shaft. An optical transmitter directs light from a laser source to impinge at an angle sequentially on the reflective surfaces as the shaft rotates, and a plurality of optical receivers spaced from one another each receive the light reflected from a respective one of the mirror surfaces and direct the reflected light to a respective one of the engine cylinders.

column12: Method and system for configuring and scheduling security audits of a computer network
column13: Managing the selection and scheduling of security audits run on a computing network. The computer network is surveyed by a security audit system to determine the function and relative importance of the elements in the network. Based on function and priority, a more thorough type of security audit is selected to run against each of the network elements by the security audit system. The security audit can also be automatically scheduled based on the information gathered from the survey. Once the system runs the security audit, a vulnerability assessment can be calculated for each element in the network. The vulnerability assessment can be presented in a format that facilitates interpretation and response by someone operating the system. The vulnerability assessment can also be used to configure and schedule future security audits.

column12: Apparatus and method for the detection and treatment of arrhythmias using a neural network.
column13: An apparatus and method for the detection and treatment of arrhythmias using a processor having a neural network (21) with a hierarchical arrangement including a first lower level (21A) for classifying individual waveforms, a second higher level (21B) for diagnosing detected arrhythmias and a third higher level (21C) for the application of therapy in response to a diagnosed arrhythmia. The neural network (21) may be a back propogation neural network or an associative memory type neural network. The arrhythmias detected may be at least one of bradycardia, tachycardia and fibrillation. The apparatus may include a cardioverting/defibrillating packmaker (15). In general, the apparatus acquires physiological signals representative of heart activity in a patient. A neural network (21) receives the physiological signals and determines if any arrhythmia is present, and if present, selects therapy to be applied to the heart. A therapy generator then applies the therapy selected by the neural network (21). The physioligical signals may be processed or unprocessed ECG signal, signals indicative of the properties of the blood, and blood flow signals or signals representative of ventricular wall impedance or ventricular volume.

column12: Apparatus and method for the detection and treatment of arrhythmias using a neural network
column13: An apparatus and method for the detection and treatment of arrhythmias using a processor having a neural network with a hierarchical arrangement including a first lower level for classifying individual waveforms, a second higher level for diagnosing detected arrhythmias and a third higher level for the application of therapy in response to a diagnosed arrhythmia. The neural network may be a back propogation neural network or an associative memory type neural network. The arrhythmias detected may be at least one of bradycardia, tachycardia and fibrillation. The apparatus may include a cardioverting/defibrillating pacemaker. In general, the apparatus acquires physiological signals representative of heart activity in a patient. A neural network receives the physiological signals and determines if any arrhythmia is present, and if present, selects therapy to be applied to the heart. A therapy generator then applies the therapy selected by the neural network. The physiological signals may be processed or unprocessed ECG signal, signals indicative of the properties of the blood including the presence of gases, blood temperature, and blood flow signals or signals representative of ventricular wall impedance or ventricular volume.

column12: DISTRIBUTOR FOR ENGINE WITH LASER IGNITION
column13: A distributor is described for a multi-cylinder laser ignited internal combustion engine. The distributor includes a shaft rotatable by the engine and a plurality of flat reflective surfaces on the shaft. The surfaces lie in planes normal to the axis of rotation of the shaft and are axially staggered from one another along the length of the shaft. An optical transmitter directs light from a laser source to impinge at an angle sequentially on the reflective surfaces as the shaft rotates, and a plurality of optical receivers spaced from one another each receive the light reflected from a respective one of the mirror surfaces and direct the reflected light to a respective one of the engine cylinders.

column12: Method and system for configuring and scheduling security audits of a computer network
column13: Managing the selection and scheduling of security audits run on a computing network. The computer network is surveyed by a security audit system to determine the function and relative importance of the elements in the network. Based on function and priority, a more thorough type of security audit is selected to run against each of the network elements by the security audit system. The security audit can also be automatically scheduled based on the information gathered from the survey. Once the system runs the security audit, a vulnerability assessment can be calculated for each element in the network. The vulnerability assessment can be presented in a format that facilitates interpretation and response by someone operating the system. The vulnerability assessment can also be used to configure and schedule future security audits.

column13: The present invention relates to an odor absorbing composition, which is safe for use on human skin, comprising from 0.1 % to 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from 0.1 % to 36 %, by weight of the composition, of an oil phase selected from the group consisting of emollients, moisturizers, and skin protectants; an emulsifier; and an aqueous carrier. column12: Composições perfumadas e em duas fases para redução do odor corporal e métodos de uso das mesmas
column13: Patente de Invenção: <B>"COMPOSIçõES PERFUMADAS E EM DUAS FASES PARA REDUçãO DO ODOR CORPORAL E MéTODOS DE USO DAS MESMAS"<D>. A presente invenção se refere a composições para absorção de odor e a seu uso sobre a pele. As composições compreendem de cerca de 0,1% a 5% em peso da composição de ciclodextrina não-complexada solubilizada solúvel em água; de cerca de 0,004% a cerca de 2% em peso da composição de uma composição de perfume; e um veículo aquoso. As composições também podem compreender ou uma dimeticona de baixo peso molecular ou uma fase oleosa selecionada do grupo consistindo em emolientes, umidificadores, protetores da pele e misturas dos mesmos e um ou mais tensoativos. As composições para absorção de odor da presente invenção também podem, de preferência, conter uma quantidade efetiva de antimicrobianos solúveis em água e/ou hidrofóbicos. A presente invenção também se refere às composições para absorção de odor depositadas sobre um dispositivo flexível de dispersão.

column12: COMPOSITIONS FOR REDUCING ODOR ON SKIN
column13: The present invention relates to an aqueous odor-absorbing composition which is safe for use on human skin comprising from about 0.1 % to about 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.5 % to about 30 %, by weight of the composition, of a linear dimethicone having a nominal viscosity of 350 centistokes or less; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can also comprise one or more of the following optional components: low molecular weight polyols; water-soluble antimicrobial preservatives; zinc salts; water-soluble polymers; soluble carbonate and/or bicarbonate salts; chelating agents; zeolites; activated carbon; and mixtures thereof. The present invention also relates the use of the aforementioned compositions in reducing body, vaginal, and or environmental odors on skin. The composition can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.

column12: Systems and methods for automatic submission, audit and adjustment of mortgage insurance claims
column13: Systems and methods are described for automatically processing mortgage insurance claims. In one described system, a central server computer receives inputs from, and provides outputs to, a servicer terminal connected into a network. The servicer terminal captures data from a servicer submitting a mortgage insurance claim. A claims database is connected into the network, containing data relating to the mortgage insurance claim. A claim audit rulebase is connected into the network, for automatically performing an audit and adjustment of the submitted mortgage insurance claim. The system automatically provides results of the audit and adjustment to the servicer at the servicer terminal, and presents the servicer with an option to interact with a claim representative to resolve any issues.

column12: Odor absorbing aqueous composition, a pre-formed odor absorbing wipe and process for preparing such odor absorbing aqueous composition
column13: In the present invention there is disclosed an aqueous odor absorbing composition comprising: (a) from 0.1 to 5 percent by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; (b) an aqueous carrier; (c) from 0.1 to 36 percent by weight of the composition, of an oil phase being selected from the group consisting of softening agents, moistening agents, and akin protectants; and (d) an emulsifier, wherein the aqueous composition is safe for use on human skin. In the present invention there is also claimed a pre-formed, odor absorbing wipe that contains the aqueous composition according to the invention deposited on the wipe which further comprises a flexible dispensing means for release of the deposited aqueous composition. A process for making an aqueous odor absorbing composition comprises the steps of: (a) making a mixture by mixing an emulsifier, an oil phase, and an aqueous phase until the mixture is homogenous; (b) making a second mixture by adding cyclodextrin to the mixture of step (a) with mixing until the cyclodextrin dissolves and the resulting mixture is homogenous.

column12: Blandinger for Õ nedsette lukt pÕ huden
column13: Vandig luktabsorberende sammensetning som er sikker å bruke på menneskets hud, omfattende 0,1-5% solubilisert, vann- løselig, ikke-kompleksdannet cyklodekstrin, beregnet på vekten av sammensetningen; 0,5-30% lineært dimethicon som har en nominell viskositet på 350 cSt eller mindre, bereg- net på vekten av sammensetningen; og en vandig bærer. Sam- mensetningene kan også omfatte en eller flere av de føl- gende valgfrie komponenter: polyoler med lav molekylvekt, vannløselige antimikrobielle konserveringsmidler, sink- salter, vannløselige polymerer, løselige karbonat- og/eller bikarbonatsalter, chelateringsmidler, zeolitter, aktivert karbon og blandinger derav. Også anvendelse av de oven- nevnte sammensetninger ved nedsettelse av kroppslukt, vagi- nal lukt og/eller miljølukt på huden. Sammensetningen kan påføres direkte i form av en spray, helles fra en flaske og påføres med hånden, eller påføres ved hjelp av en serviett.

column12: Composições para reduzir o odor na pele
column13: The present invention relates to an aqueous odor-absorbing composition which is safe for use on human skin comprising from about 0.1 % to about 5 %, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; from about 0.5 % to about 30 %, by weight of the composition, of a linear dimethicone having a nominal viscosity of 350 centistokes or less; and an aqueous carrier. The compositions can also comprise one or more of the following optional components: low molecular weight polyols; water-soluble antimicrobial preservatives; zinc salts; water-soluble polymers; soluble carbonate and/or bicarbonate salts; chelating agents; zeolites; activated carbon; and mixtures thereof. The present invention also relates the use of the aforementioned compositions in reducing body, vaginal, and or environmental odors on skin. The composition can be applied directly as a spray, poured from a bottle and applied by hand, or applied via a wipe.
column15: TRINH TOAN;;DODD MICHAEL THOMAS;;BARTOLO ROBERT GREGORY;;LUCAS JULIET MARIE;;BUCKNER ROBIN YAGER;;KAJS THERESA MARIE

column12: COMPOSITION FOR REDUCING ODOR ON SKIN
column13: An aqueous odour absorbing composition comprises: (a) 0.1-5 wt.% of solubilised, water-soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; (b) 0.5-30 wt.% of a linear dimethicone having a nominal viscosity of 350 centistokes or less; optionally (c) an effective amount of solubilised, water-soluble, antimicrobial preservative; and (d) an aqueous carrier. The composition is safe for use on skin. Also claimed is a pre-formed wipe composition where the claimed composition is deposited on a wipe, which comprises a flexible dispensing means.

column12: Multi-phasic implant device for the repair or replacement of cartilage tissue
column13: H:sxd\lnterwoven\NRPortbl\DCC\SXD\9883489 1docx-24/03/2016 Tissue implants prepared for the repair of tissues, especially avascular tissues such as cartilage. One embodiment presents an electric potential capable of receiving and accumulating desirable factors or molecules from surrounding fluid when exposed to dynamic loading. In another embodiment the implant promotes tissue conduction by retarding, restricting and controlling cellular invasion through use of gradients until competent tissue forms. Further embodiments of the tissue implants may be formed into a multi-phasic device that provides deep tissue mechanical stimulus by conduction of mechanical and fluid forces experienced at the surface of the implant. column12: METHODS AND COMPOSITIONS FOR REDUCING BODY ODOR
column13: PURPOSE: A cyclodextrin-containing composition for the manufacture of an odor absorbing composition is provided, which is safe for use on skin, for controlling environmental malodors on skin and for reducing body odor and/or vaginal odor. CONSTITUTION: An aqueous odor absorbing composition comprises: a) from 0.1% to 5%, by weight of the composition, of solubilized, water soluble, uncomplexed cyclodextrin; b) an aqueous carrier; c) from 0.1% to 36%, by weight of the composition, of an oil phase selected from the group consisting of emollients, moisturizers, and skin protectants; and d. an emulsifier; and wherein the composition is safe for use on human skin.

column12: SPECIMEN REVIEW STATION
column13: A specimen review station (50) includes a vibration isolation table (64) that supports storage (80) and transportation (82, 84) equipments for a semiconductor wafer (54) and an optical system (58) for viewing microscopic regions of the patterned surface of the wafer. The optical system (58) includes an image extender (88) that enables an operator sitting on an adjustable chair (107) to view the wafer from a distance, thereby facilitating remote transportation and inspection of relatively large diameter wafers and reducing operator contamination of the wafer. An operator table (66) supports control equipments (96, 98, 100), which the operator uses to control the functions of the specimen review station. The vibration isolation table and the operator table are spatially isolated from each other in that they are connected only by the floor (70) that supports both of them. The vibration isolation table is, therefore, affected by neither floor vibrations resulting from normal building movement associated with manufacturing operations nor operator contact with the operator table.
